No, they are semantically the same. You can also return the condition instead of using an if clause as it will evaluate to a boolean anyway:

    return (33 &lt;= cp &lt;= 47) or (58 &lt;= cp &lt;= 64) or (91 &lt;= cp &lt;= 96) or (123 &lt;= cp &lt;= 126)

They (Google AI engineers) may not have known about chained comparisons or they [wanted it to perform _slightly_ better](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/48375753/why-are-chained-operator-expressions-slower-than-their-expanded-equivalent).

